To change your guest account to an admin or full user account on the Chromebook, here’s what you need to do:The Owner account is the first Google account that was used to set up the Chromebook. Only that Owner has full admin rights to manage device settings and users.You cannot convert a guest account into an admin. Guest mode is always limited and temporary, designed for quick use without saving data or permissions.To have admin access and proper permissions, the Chromebook Owner (your son) needs to:Add your Google account as a new regular user on the Chromebook.Alternatively, sign out of guest mode and sign into the Chromebook using your own Google account that the Owner adds.Manage user permissions via Settings → People → Manage other people. From there, the Owner can allow your account to sign in and manage settings.If your son’s Google account is the Owner, only he can add or remove users or change who can sign in. You’ll need him to assist by logging in as Owner.If the Chromebook is managed by a school or organization, you may be restricted from adding users — in that case, contact the administrator.Summary:Guest accounts are always limited and cannot be promoted.The Owner account (first account set up) controls admin rights and user management.Your son, as the owner, must add your account as a regular user with proper sign-in.You should then sign into the Chromebook directly with your Google account for full permissions.After that, your Linux environment will retain installed packages and allow app building.Once your son sets up a full user account for you and you’re signed in with it, let me know. Then I will guide you step-by-step through the Node/npm installation and React Native setup with full permissions.This is the necessary step to enable smooth development on the Chromebook. If you want, I can help draft an exact procedure you can give to your son to simplify this process.
